<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="186" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,900,2043]" pageId="1" pageNumber="186">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,972,998]" pageId="1" pageNumber="186">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Head with hairy eyes (
<figureCitation box="[586,659,972,999]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1911,1935]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,417,1888]" captionTargetId="figure-83@2.[151,1435,417,1888]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Elasmarion longipes sp. nov., female paratypes; 1 body in dorsal view; 2 body in lateral view; 3 head in frontal view; 4 right fore wing; 5 left fore leg; 6 left hind leg." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4424043" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4424043/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="186">Figs 3</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[673,689,973,999]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1957,1981]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,705,1933]" captionTargetId="figure-220@3.[151,1435,705,1933]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7–10. Elasmarion longipes sp. nov., paratypes; 7 head+mesosoma in dorsal view, female; 8 head+antenna in lateral view, female; 9 antenna in lateral view, male; 10 left mandible, female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4424047" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4424047/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="186">7</figureCitation>
); antennae attached just below lower level of eyes (
<figureCitation box="[1280,1348,972,999]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1911,1935]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,417,1888]" captionTargetId="figure-83@2.[151,1435,417,1888]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Elasmarion longipes sp. nov., female paratypes; 1 body in dorsal view; 2 body in lateral view; 3 head in frontal view; 4 right fore wing; 5 left fore leg; 6 left hind leg." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4424043" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4424043/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="186">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
); malar sulcus absent (
<figureCitation box="[314,381,1008,1035]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1957,1981]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,705,1933]" captionTargetId="figure-220@3.[151,1435,705,1933]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7–10. Elasmarion longipes sp. nov., paratypes; 7 head+mesosoma in dorsal view, female; 8 head+antenna in lateral view, female; 9 antenna in lateral view, male; 10 left mandible, female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4424047" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4424047/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="186">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
); frons and vertex with scattered long and strong setae (
<figureCitation box="[1006,1074,1008,1035]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1911,1935]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,417,1888]" captionTargetId="figure-83@2.[151,1435,417,1888]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Elasmarion longipes sp. nov., female paratypes; 1 body in dorsal view; 2 body in lateral view; 3 head in frontal view; 4 right fore wing; 5 left fore leg; 6 left hind leg." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4424043" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4424043/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="186">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Antenna in both sexes with six flagellomeres: three funiculars and three claval segments (
<figureCitation box="[803,904,1044,1071]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1957,1981]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,705,1933]" captionTargetId="figure-220@3.[151,1435,705,1933]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7–10. Elasmarion longipes sp. nov., paratypes; 7 head+mesosoma in dorsal view, female; 8 head+antenna in lateral view, female; 9 antenna in lateral view, male; 10 left mandible, female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4424047" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4424047/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="186">Figs 8, 9</figureCitation>
); male flagellomeres unbranched (
<figureCitation box="[1293,1361,1044,1071]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1957,1981]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,705,1933]" captionTargetId="figure-220@3.[151,1435,705,1933]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7–10. Elasmarion longipes sp. nov., paratypes; 7 head+mesosoma in dorsal view, female; 8 head+antenna in lateral view, female; 9 antenna in lateral view, male; 10 left mandible, female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4424047" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4424047/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="186">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
). Thoracic dorsum with rather strong reticulation (
<figureCitation box="[661,733,1080,1107]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1911,1935]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,417,1888]" captionTargetId="figure-83@2.[151,1435,417,1888]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Elasmarion longipes sp. nov., female paratypes; 1 body in dorsal view; 2 body in lateral view; 3 head in frontal view; 4 right fore wing; 5 left fore leg; 6 left hind leg." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4424043" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4424043/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="186">Figs 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[748,764,1081,1107]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1957,1981]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,705,1933]" captionTargetId="figure-220@3.[151,1435,705,1933]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7–10. Elasmarion longipes sp. nov., paratypes; 7 head+mesosoma in dorsal view, female; 8 head+antenna in lateral view, female; 9 antenna in lateral view, male; 10 left mandible, female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4424047" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4424047/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="186">7</figureCitation>
); mesoscutum with notauli absent, midlobe with numerous long and strong setae scattered over the whole surface; mesoscutellum without longitudinal grooves, with two pairs of long and strong setae. Propodeum with an incomplete median carina, missing in posterior part (
<figureCitation box="[1235,1303,1152,1179]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1957,1981]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,705,1933]" captionTargetId="figure-220@3.[151,1435,705,1933]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7–10. Elasmarion longipes sp. nov., paratypes; 7 head+mesosoma in dorsal view, female; 8 head+antenna in lateral view, female; 9 antenna in lateral view, male; 10 left mandible, female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4424047" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4424047/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="186">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). Fore wing with postmarginal vein 1.2× as long as stigmal vein (
<figureCitation box="[747,817,1188,1215]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1911,1935]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,417,1888]" captionTargetId="figure-83@2.[151,1435,417,1888]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Elasmarion longipes sp. nov., female paratypes; 1 body in dorsal view; 2 body in lateral view; 3 head in frontal view; 4 right fore wing; 5 left fore leg; 6 left hind leg." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4424043" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4424043/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="186">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Fore leg with tibial spur strong, as long as basitarsus, and slightly bent, tarsus short with tarsomeres subequal in length (
<figureCitation box="[882,949,1224,1251]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1911,1935]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,417,1888]" captionTargetId="figure-83@2.[151,1435,417,1888]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Elasmarion longipes sp. nov., female paratypes; 1 body in dorsal view; 2 body in lateral view; 3 head in frontal view; 4 right fore wing; 5 left fore leg; 6 left hind leg." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4424043" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4424043/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="186">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
); mid and hind legs long and pointing backwards in dead specimens (
<figureCitation box="[444,512,1260,1287]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1911,1935]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,417,1888]" captionTargetId="figure-83@2.[151,1435,417,1888]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Elasmarion longipes sp. nov., female paratypes; 1 body in dorsal view; 2 body in lateral view; 3 head in frontal view; 4 right fore wing; 5 left fore leg; 6 left hind leg." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4424043" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4424043/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="186">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), each with basitarsus very long, as long as combined length of T2–4 (
<figureCitation box="[1297,1365,1260,1287]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1911,1935]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,417,1888]" captionTargetId="figure-83@2.[151,1435,417,1888]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Elasmarion longipes sp. nov., female paratypes; 1 body in dorsal view; 2 body in lateral view; 3 head in frontal view; 4 right fore wing; 5 left fore leg; 6 left hind leg." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4424043" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4424043/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="186">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
); hind coxa large (
<figureCitation box="[281,382,1296,1323]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1911,1935]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,417,1888]" captionTargetId="figure-83@2.[151,1435,417,1888]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Elasmarion longipes sp. nov., female paratypes; 1 body in dorsal view; 2 body in lateral view; 3 head in frontal view; 4 right fore wing; 5 left fore leg; 6 left hind leg." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4424043" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4424043/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="186">Figs 2, 6</figureCitation>
). Petiole very short, just a narrow strip. Female and male are very similar.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="186" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,900,2043]" pageId="1" pageNumber="186">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1332,1358]" pageId="1" pageNumber="186">Description</emphasis>
. Head with eyes strongly hairy; malar sulcus absent; clypeus not delimited, clypeal area reticulate with ventral margin straight; antennal scrobes undelimited and smooth; occipital margin with a sharp edge; occiput concave in dorsal view, with strong reticulation; frons and vertex with scattered long and strong setae. Antenna inserted just below lower level of eyes, scape short and not reaching anterior ocellus; scape wider in male; with six flagellomeres: three funiculars and three claval segments, female with one large anellus, no anelli visible in male; male with unbranched flagellomeres. Pronotum short, without a carina along anterior margin of pronotal collar. Mesoscutum with rather strong reticulation throughout; midlobe with numerous long and strong setae scattered over the whole surface; notauli absent. Mesoscutellum with rather strong reticulation throughout, without longitudinal grooves, with two pairs of setae, one pair attached close to anterior margin, and one pair attached posterolaterally. Axillae with rather weak reticulation, advanced forward by half their length in front of transscutal articulation. Dorsellum with rather weak reticulation and with posterior margin rounded triangular. Propodeum with an incomplete median carina, missing in posterior part, with very weak reticulation on either side of median carina; callus with weak reticulation and with 4–6 setae. Fore wing with 7–9 setae on dorsal surface of submarginal vein; speculum absent to small, closed below and towards base of wing; costal cell with a complete row of setae on dorsal surface along anterior margin, and with an irregular but complete row of setae on ventral surface; with a row of admarginal setae along entire marginal vein on ventral side of membrane; postmarginal vein 1.2× as long as stigmal vein. Fore leg with a short tarsus with all four tarsomeres subequal in length; mid and hind legs with long tarsi with basitarsus very long, as long as combined length of T2–4: hind leg with coxa large but not flattened, tibia with two strong tibial spurs. Petiole very short, barely visible in dorsal view. Gastral tergites weakly sclerotized, ±shrivelled even when dried in a critical point drier, with very weak reticulation and shiny.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
